{"title_page": "Lisa Lillien", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Lisa Lillien\n| birth_place        = [[United States]]\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1969|12|31}}\n| residence          = \n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n* Cook\n* Book\n* Author\n* Blogger\n* TV Personality}}\n| spouse             = [[Dan Schneider (TV producer)|Dan Schneider]] (m. 2002)\n}}\n\n'''Lisa Lillien''' (born December 31, 1969) is an American entrepreneur. She is the creator of the [[Hungry Girl]] brand, including email-subscription, cookbooks, low-calorie recipes, and [[life hacks|life-hacks]].<ref name=\"Huffington Post\">{{cite web|last=Rogers|first=John|title=Lisa Lillien of The 'Hungry Girl' Empire Reveals How She Stopped Yo-Yo Dieting For Good|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/11/18/lisa-lillien-hungry-girl-_n_2154976.html|publisher=Huffington Post|accessdate=September 3, 2014}}{Dead link|date=February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nLillien's roots are in magazines<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.albany.edu/ualbanymagazine/spring18_lillien-back-to-her-roots.shtml|title=Back to Her Roots|first=University at Albany|last=Magazine|website=www.albany.edu|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\nand, more generally, entertainment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://orjewishlife.com/noshing-with-hungry-girl-lisa-lillien/ |title=Noshing with \"Hungry Girl\" Lisa Lillien &#124; Oregon Jewish Life |publisher=Orjewishlife.com |date=2018-12-21 |accessdate=2020-04-18}}</ref> She grew up on Long Island and identifies as Jewish (\"a nice Jewish girl from Long Island\"). She graduated from [[Lawrence High School (Cedarhurst, New York)]] in 1983.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/14/dining/14hungry.html|title=Hungry Girl Offers a Real Take on Diet Foods|first=Julia|last=Moskin|date=July 13, 2010|accessdate=April 14, 2020|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> She does not have a degree in nutrition, but uses the [[neologism]] ''foodologist'' due to obsession with food.<ref name=\"Hungry Girl\">{{cite web|title=Who Is Hungry Girl?|url=https://www.hungry-girl.com/who-is-hungry-girl|publisher=Hungry Girl|accessdate=September 3, 2014}}</ref>\nShe did, however, receive a B.A. in communication from Univ. at Albany (SUNY) in 1987. Directly from college she became editor-in-chief at ''Tutti Frutti'' (teen-fan magazine, Jimmijack Publishing, 1987-1991).<ref>{{cite web|author=Your name here |url=https://www.amazon.com/Tutti-Frutti-November-Centerfold-Pinups/dp/B07PS6NTPY |title=Tutti Frutti November 1991 Luke Perry Centerfold, Pinups: Lisa Lillien: Amazon.com: Books |publisher=Amazon.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Business===\nFor five years, Lillien was online executive producer for [[TV Land]] and director of convergence development at [[Nickelodeon]] online. Next she was a producer for new media at [[Telepictures]] ([[Warner Brothers|Warner Bros.]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.albany.edu/news/43805.php|title='Hungry Girl' and Alumna Lisa Lillien \u201987 Headlines UAlbany Homecoming and Family Weekend, Oct. 18 - 20 - University at Albany-SUNY|website=www.albany.edu|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\nShe quit her job and started the Hungry Girl brand in 2004, with a weekly email (originally Tips and Tricks ... for Hungry Chicks). She averages over a million subscribers.<ref name=\"Diets in Review\">{{cite web|title=Lisa Lillien is No Nutritionist, Just Hungry for Good Nutrition|url=https://dietsinreview.com/diet_column/07/lisa-lillien-is-no-nutritionist-just-hungry-for-good-nutrition/|publisher=Diets in Review|accessdate=September 3, 2014}}</ref> The content consists mainly of recipes and [[life hacks|life-hacks]],<ref name=\"Belief Net\">{{cite web|last1=Deanna Schwartz|first1=Daylle|title=Interview with Hungry Girl's Lisa Lillien|url=https://www.beliefnet.com/columnists/lessonsfromarecoveringdoormat/2008/05/interview-with-hungry-girls-lisa-lillien.html|publisher=Belief Net|accessdate=September 3, 2014}}</ref> written in a ''pink, exclamation-point, LOL'' style; or as Lillien once put it, \"getting excited over silly things [...] When I launched Hungry Girl, I wanted it to be the same...writing style[:] conversational and excited, [like] writing about teen stars, and pop stars...\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metro.us/hungry-girl-lisa-lillien-brings-her-cooking-show-to-the-food-network/|title='Hungry Girl' Lisa Lillien brings her cooking show to the Food Network|website=Metro US|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nRegular advertisers across media have included [[WW International|Weight Watchers]], [[Dreyers]] light ice cream, and [[General Mills]], later including [[Green Giant]], [[Quaker]], [[The Laughing Cow|Laughing Cow]] cheeses, and [[Beyond Better Foods]].{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Media===\nAs a writer, Lillien has had a weekly column on the [[WW International|Weight Watchers]] website and has written for ''[[Redbook]]'' magazine. She has appeared on cooking shows like ''[[Rachael Ray (TV series)|Rachael Ray]]''.<ref name=\"Diets in Review\" />\n\nIn 2009, Lillien responded to [[Patti Labelle]]'s audition-call to be her personal chef on the ''[[Tyra Banks]] [[Tyra Banks Show|Show]]'' (NB: Labelle is herself a renowned and published cook). \nAccording to Lillien, it turned into a \"smackdown\"<ref>[https://twitter.com/hungrygirl/status/1279951928 ]{{dead link|date=April 2020}}</ref> and became a point-of-discussion regarding social interaction, passive-aggressiveness, condescension, even microaggression/racism.<refhttps://dandygoat.com/11-butt-numbingly-offensive-words-you-need-to-ban-from-your-vocabulary</ref><ref>[https://twitter.com/hungrygirl/status/1279951928?lang=en ]{{dead link|date=April 2020}}</ref>\nOn 7 Mar. 2020, ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' presented a sketch parodying the interaction, featuring [[Ego Nwodim]] (as a famous singer), guest host [[Daniel Craig]] (as the guest cook), and [[Aidy Bryant]] (as the show host).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DSj3hL2O8rY |title=Daytime Show - SNL |publisher=YouTube |date=2020-03-07 |accessdate=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011 and 2012, Triage Entertainment produced 36 episodes of a Hungry Girl program; they aired on Cooking Channel and Food Network. The recipes of the 2012 season remain online.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foodnetwork.com/shows/hungry-girl/episodes|title=Hungry Girl Episodes|website=Food Network|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Meredith Corporation began a quarterly ''Hungry Girl'' magazine in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foliomag.com/magazine-review-hungry-girl-leaves-starving-content-better-design/|title=Magazine Review: Hungry Girl Leaves Me Starving for More Content and Better Design|date=January 18, 2018|website=Folio:|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\n*''Hungry Girl Clean & Hungry: Easy All-Natural Recipes for Healthy Eating in the Real World'' (April 5, 2016)\n*''The Hungry Girl Diet Cookbook: Healthy Recipes for Mix-n-Match Meals & Snacks'' (December 29, 2015)\n*''The Hungry Girl Diet: Big Portions. Big Results. Drop 10 Pounds in 4 Weeks'' (March 25, 2014)\n*''Hungry Girl 200 Under 200 Just Desserts: 200 Recipes Under 200 Calories'' (May 7, 2013)\n*''Hungry Girl to the Max!: The Ultimate Guilt-Free Cookbook'' (October 16, 2012)\n*''By Lisa Lillien \u2013 Hungry Girl 300 Under 300: 300 Breakfast, Lunch & Dinner Dishes Under 300 Calories'' (February 27, 2011)\n*''Hungry Girl 300 Under 300: 300 Breakfast, Lunch & Dinner Dishes Under 300 Calories'' (March 29, 2011)\n*''Hungry Girl Supermarket Survival: Aisle by Aisle, HG-Style!'' (October 11, 2011)\n*''Hungry Girl 1-2-3: The Easiest, Most Delicious, Guilt-Free Recipes on the Planet'' (March 30, 2010)\n*''Hungry Girl Happy Hour: 75 Recipes for Amazingly Fantastic Guilt-Free Cocktails and Party Foods'' (June 22, 2010)\n*''Hungry Girl: 200 Under 200: 200 Recipes Under 200 Calories'' (April 14, 2009)\n*''Hungry Girl: The Official Survival Guides'' (April 14, 2009)\n*''Hungry Girl Chew the Right Thing: Supreme Makeovers for 50 Foods You Crave'' (December 8, 2009)\n*''Hungry Girl: Recipes and Survival Strategies for Guilt-Free Eating in the Real World'' (April 29, 2008)\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 2002, Lillien married writer/producer [[Dan Schneider (TV producer)|Dan Schneider]]. They have a dog, Lolly, and live in Encino, CA.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/food/la-fo-hungrygirl22-2009jul22-story.html|title=Hungry Girl delivers|date=September 16, 2014|website=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|https://www.hungry-girl.com/}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lillien, Lisa}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:American cookbook writers]]\n[[Category:American women non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Women cookbook writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Lisa Lillien\n| birth_place        = [[United States]]\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1969|12|31}}\n| residence          = \n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n* Cook\n* Book\n* Author\n* Blogger\n* TV Personality}}\n| spouse             = [[Dan Schneider (TV producer)|Dan Schneider]] (m. 2002)\n}}\n\n'''Lisa Lillien''' (born December 31, 1969) is an American entrepreneur. She is the creator of the [[Hungry Girl]] brand, including email-subscription, cookbooks, low-calorie recipes, and [[life hacks|life-hacks]].<ref name=\"Huffington Post\">{{cite web|last=Rogers|first=John|title=Lisa Lillien of The 'Hungry Girl' Empire Reveals How She Stopped Yo-Yo Dieting For Good|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/11/18/lisa-lillien-hungry-girl-_n_2154976.html|publisher=Huffington Post|accessdate=September 3, 2014}}{Dead link|date=February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nLillien's roots are in magazines\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.albany.edu/ualbanymagazine/spring18_lillien-back-to-her-roots.shtml|title=Back to Her Roots|first=University at Albany|last=Magazine|website=www.albany.edu|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\nand, more generally, entertainment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://orjewishlife.com/noshing-with-hungry-girl-lisa-lillien/ |title=Noshing with \"Hungry Girl\" Lisa Lillien &#124; Oregon Jewish Life |publisher=Orjewishlife.com |date=2018-12-21 |accessdate=2020-04-18}}</ref> She grew up on Long Island and identifies as Jewish (\"a nice Jewish girl from Long Island\"). She graduated from [[Lawrence High School (Cedarhurst, New York)]] in 1983.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/14/dining/14hungry.html|title=Hungry Girl Offers a Real Take on Diet Foods|first=Julia|last=Moskin|date=July 13, 2010|accessdate=April 14, 2020|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> She does not have a degree in nutrition, but uses the [[neologism]] ''foodologist'' due to obsession with food.<ref name=\"Hungry Girl\">{{cite web|title=Who Is Hungry Girl?|url=https://www.hungry-girl.com/who-is-hungry-girl|publisher=Hungry Girl|accessdate=September 3, 2014}}</ref>\nShe did, however, receive a B.A. in communication from Univ. at Albany (SUNY) in 1987. Directly from college she became editor-in-chief at ''Tutti Frutti'' (teen-fan magazine, Jimmijack Publishing, 1987-1991).<ref>{{cite web|author=Your name here |url=https://www.amazon.com/Tutti-Frutti-November-Centerfold-Pinups/dp/B07PS6NTPY |title=Tutti Frutti November 1991 Luke Perry Centerfold, Pinups: Lisa Lillien: Amazon.com: Books |publisher=Amazon.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Business===\nFor five years, Lillien was online executive producer for [[TV Land]] and director of convergence development at [[Nickelodeon]] online. Next she was a producer for new media at [[Telepictures]] ([[Warner Brothers|Warner Bros.]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.albany.edu/news/43805.php|title='Hungry Girl' and Alumna Lisa Lillien \u201987 Headlines UAlbany Homecoming and Family Weekend, Oct. 18 - 20 - University at Albany-SUNY|website=www.albany.edu|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\nShe quit her job and started the Hungry Girl brand in 2004, with a weekly email (originally Tips and Tricks ... for Hungry Chicks). She averages over a million subscribers.<ref name=\"Diets in Review\">{{cite web|title=Lisa Lillien is No Nutritionist, Just Hungry for Good Nutrition|url=https://dietsinreview.com/diet_column/07/lisa-lillien-is-no-nutritionist-just-hungry-for-good-nutrition/|publisher=Diets in Review|accessdate=September 3, 2014}}</ref> The content consists mainly of recipes and [[life hacks|life-hacks]],<ref name=\"Belief Net\">{{cite web|last1=Deanna Schwartz|first1=Daylle|title=Interview with Hungry Girl's Lisa Lillien|url=https://www.beliefnet.com/columnists/lessonsfromarecoveringdoormat/2008/05/interview-with-hungry-girls-lisa-lillien.html|publisher=Belief Net|accessdate=September 3, 2014}}</ref> written in a ''pink, exclamation-point, LOL'' style; or as Lillien once put it, \"getting excited over silly things [...] When I launched Hungry Girl, I wanted it to be the same...writing style[:] conversational and excited, [like] writing about teen stars, and pop stars...\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metro.us/hungry-girl-lisa-lillien-brings-her-cooking-show-to-the-food-network/|title='Hungry Girl' Lisa Lillien brings her cooking show to the Food Network|website=Metro US|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nRegular advertisers across media have included [[WW International|Weight Watchers]], [[Dreyers]] light ice cream, and [[General Mills]], later including [[Green Giant]], [[Quaker]], [[The Laughing Cow|Laughing Cow]] cheeses, and [[Beyond Better Foods]].{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Media===\nAs a writer, Lillien has had a weekly column on the [[WW International|Weight Watchers]] website and has written for ''[[Redbook]]'' magazine. She has appeared on cooking shows like ''[[Rachael Ray (TV series)|Rachael Ray]]''.<ref name=\"Diets in Review\" />\n\nIn 2009, Lillien responded to [[Patti Labelle]]'s audition-call to be her personal chef on the ''[[Tyra Banks]] [[Tyra Banks Show|Show]]'' (NB: Labelle is herself a renowned and published cook). \nAccording to Lillien, it turned into a \"smackdown\"<ref>[https://twitter.com/hungrygirl/status/1279951928 ]{{dead link|date=April 2020}}</ref> and became a point-of-discussion regarding social interaction, passive-aggressiveness, condescension, even microaggression/racism.<refhttps://dandygoat.com/11-butt-numbingly-offensive-words-you-need-to-ban-from-your-vocabulary</ref><ref>[https://twitter.com/hungrygirl/status/1279951928?lang=en ]{{dead link|date=April 2020}}</ref>\nOn 7 Mar. 2020, ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' presented a sketch parodying the interaction, featuring [[Ego Nwodim]] (as a famous singer), guest host [[Daniel Craig]] (as the guest cook), and [[Aidy Bryant]] (as the show host).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DSj3hL2O8rY |title=Daytime Show - SNL |publisher=YouTube |date=2020-03-07 |accessdate=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011 and 2012, Triage Entertainment produced 36 episodes of a Hungry Girl program; they aired on Cooking Channel and Food Network. The recipes of the 2012 season remain online.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foodnetwork.com/shows/hungry-girl/episodes|title=Hungry Girl Episodes|website=Food Network|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Meredith Corporation began a quarterly ''Hungry Girl'' magazine in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foliomag.com/magazine-review-hungry-girl-leaves-starving-content-better-design/|title=Magazine Review: Hungry Girl Leaves Me Starving for More Content and Better Design|date=January 18, 2018|website=Folio:|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\n*''Hungry Girl Clean & Hungry: Easy All-Natural Recipes for Healthy Eating in the Real World'' (April 5, 2016)\n*''The Hungry Girl Diet Cookbook: Healthy Recipes for Mix-n-Match Meals & Snacks'' (December 29, 2015)\n*''The Hungry Girl Diet: Big Portions. Big Results. Drop 10 Pounds in 4 Weeks'' (March 25, 2014)\n*''Hungry Girl 200 Under 200 Just Desserts: 200 Recipes Under 200 Calories'' (May 7, 2013)\n*''Hungry Girl to the Max!: The Ultimate Guilt-Free Cookbook'' (October 16, 2012)\n*''By Lisa Lillien \u2013 Hungry Girl 300 Under 300: 300 Breakfast, Lunch & Dinner Dishes Under 300 Calories'' (February 27, 2011)\n*''Hungry Girl 300 Under 300: 300 Breakfast, Lunch & Dinner Dishes Under 300 Calories'' (March 29, 2011)\n*''Hungry Girl Supermarket Survival: Aisle by Aisle, HG-Style!'' (October 11, 2011)\n*''Hungry Girl 1-2-3: The Easiest, Most Delicious, Guilt-Free Recipes on the Planet'' (March 30, 2010)\n*''Hungry Girl Happy Hour: 75 Recipes for Amazingly Fantastic Guilt-Free Cocktails and Party Foods'' (June 22, 2010)\n*''Hungry Girl: 200 Under 200: 200 Recipes Under 200 Calories'' (April 14, 2009)\n*''Hungry Girl: The Official Survival Guides'' (April 14, 2009)\n*''Hungry Girl Chew the Right Thing: Supreme Makeovers for 50 Foods You Crave'' (December 8, 2009)\n*''Hungry Girl: Recipes and Survival Strategies for Guilt-Free Eating in the Real World'' (April 29, 2008)\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 2002, Lillien married writer/producer [[Dan Schneider (TV producer)|Dan Schneider]]. They have a dog, Lolly, and live in Encino, CA.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/food/la-fo-hungrygirl22-2009jul22-story.html|title=Hungry Girl delivers|date=September 16, 2014|website=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|https://www.hungry-girl.com/}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lillien, Lisa}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:American cookbook writers]]\n[[Category:American women non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Women cookbook w