{"title_page": "Anifah Aman", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=May 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Malay name|Anifah|Aman}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[Malay titles#Honorary styles|Yang Berbahagia]] [[Malay titles#Datuk Sri|Datuk Seri Panglima]]\n| name             = Anifah Aman\n| native_name      = \u0627\u0646\u064a\u0641\u0647 \u0628\u0646 \u0627\u0645\u0627\u0646 @ \u062d\u0646\u064a\u0641\u0641 \u0639\u0627\u0645\u0645\u0646\n| honorific-suffix = {{small|[[Order of Kinabalu#Commander|SPDK]] [[Orders, decorations, and medals of Pahang|SSAP]] [[Orders, decorations, and medals of Pahang|DIMP]]}}\n| image            = Anifah Aman meeting Iranian FM Javad Zarif(Cropped).jpg\n| caption          =\n| office           = [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Malaysia)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]]\n| monarch = [[Mizan Zainal Abidin of Terengganu|Mizan Zainal Abidin]]<br />[[Abdul Halim of Kedah|Abdul Halim]]<br />[[Muhammad V of Kelantan|Muhammad V]]\n| term_start       = 10 April 2009\n| term_end         = 10 May 2018\n| primeminister    = [[Najib Razak]]\n| deputy           = [[Reezal Merican Naina Merican]] <br/> A. Kohillan Pillay (2009-2013) <br/> [[Lee Chee Leong]] (2009-2010) <br/> [[Richard Riot Jaem]] (2010-2013) <br/> [[Hamzah Zainudin]] (2013-2015) <br/> [[Reezal Merican Naina Merican]] (2015-2018)\n| predecessor      = [[Rais Yatim]]\n| successor        = [[Saifuddin Abdullah]]\n| constituency = [[Kimanis (federal constituency)|Kimanis]]\n| office1 = [[Ministry of Primary Industries (Malaysia)|Deputy Minister of Plantation Industries and Commodities]]\n| term_start1 = 15 December 1999\n| term_end1 = 18 March 2008 <br/> {{small|as Deputy Minister of Primary Industries : 15 December 1999-26 March 2004}}\n| minister1 = [[Lim Keng Yaik]] {{small|as Minister of Primary Industries}} (1999-2004) <br/> [[Peter Chin Fah Kui]] (2004-2008)\n| monarch1 = [[Salahuddin of Selangor|Salahuddin]]<br /> [[Sirajuddin of Perlis|Sirajuddin]]<br />Mizan Zainal Abidin\n| primeminister1 = [[Mahathir Mohamad]]<br />  [[Abdullah Ahmad Badawi]]\n| constituency1 = [[Kimanis (federal constituency)|Kimanis]]\n| successor1 = A. Kohillan Pillay\n| predecessor1 = [[Hishammuddin Hussein]]<br />{{small|as Deputy Minister of Primary Industries}}\n| constituency_MP2 = [[Kimanis (federal constituency)|Kimanis]]\n| parliament2      = Malaysian\n| term_start2      = 22 March 2004\n| term_end2        = 16 August 2019\n| majority2        = 5,108 ([[2004 Malaysian general election|2004]])<br />5,453 ([[2008 Malaysian general election|2008]])<br />5,723 ([[2013 Malaysian general election|2013]])<br />156 ([[2018 Malaysian general election|2018]])\n| predecessor4     = Nurnikman Abdullah\n| successor4       = Mohamad Alamin\n| constituency_MP5 = [[Beaufort (federal constituency)|Beaufort]]\n| parliament5      = Malaysian\n| term_start5      = 30 November 1999\n| term_end5        = 21 March 2004\n| majority5        = 6,800 ([[1999 Malaysian general election|1999]])\n| predecessor5     = Nurnikman Abdullah\n| successor5       = [[Azizah Mohd Dun]]\n| birth_name       = Anifah bin Aman @ Haniff Amman \n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1953|11|16}}\n| birth_place      = [[Keningau]], [[Crown Colony of North Borneo]]\n| residence        =\n| death_date       =\n| death_ place     =\n| party            = [[United Malays National Organisation]] (until 2018) <br /> [[Independent politician|Independent]] (2018-present)\n| otherparty       = *[[Barisan Nasional]] (BN) (until 2018)\n*[[United Alliance]] (2018-present)\n| occupation       = [[Politician]]\n| relations        = [[Musa Aman]] (elder [[Half sibling|half brother]])\n| spouse           = Siti Rubiah Abdul Samad\n| children         = 3 sons\n| alma_mater       = [[University College of Buckingham]]\n| website          =\n| footnotes        =\n}}\n'''Anifah bin Haji Aman''' ([[Jawi alphabet|Jawi]]: \u0627\u0646\u064a\u0641\u0647 \u0628\u0646 \u0627\u0645\u0627\u0646 @ \u062d\u0646\u064a\u0641\u0641 \u0639\u0627\u0645\u0645\u0646; born 16 November 1953) is a [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]] politician who had served as the [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Malaysia)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]] of Malaysia from April 2009 to May 2018. Anifah is also the former [[Dewan Rakyat|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Beaufort (federal constituency)|Beaufort]] (1999-2004) and [[Kimanis (federal constituency)|Kimanis]] (2004-2019) in [[Sabah]]. He was a former member of the [[United Malays National Organisation]] (UMNO) which is part of the [[Barisan Nasional]] (BN) coalition, until he quit to be an [[Independent politician]] in 2018.<ref name=QuitUMNO>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/09/19/anifah-i-quit-umno-in-the-interest-of-sabah-rights|title=Anifah: I quit Umno in the interest of Sabah rights|publisher= [[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|author=Muguntan Vanar|date=19 September 2018 |access-date=15 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nAnifah is married to Siti Rubiah Abdul Samad and has 3 sons. His second wife is Sophia Mohd Noor and has a daughter. He is the younger [[Half sibling|half brother]] of former [[Chief Minister of Sabah]], [[Musa Aman]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2008/03/20/dont-read-too-much-into-why-anifah-declined-post-says-big-brother-musa-aman/|title=Don\u2019t read too much into why Anifah declined post, says big brother Musa Aman|publisher=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|date=20 March 2008|accessdate=18 May 2018|quote=Sabah Chief Minister Datuk Musa Aman said his younger brother Datuk Anifah Aman had declined the Deputy Minister\u2019s post as he had served in that capacity for two terms.}}</ref> His nephew, [[Yamani Hafez Musa]] who is Musa's son; is the MP for [[Sipitang]].\n\n== Political career ==\nAnifah was first elected to Parliament in [[1999 Malaysian general election|1999 general election]], winning the seat of [[Beaufort (federal constituency)|Beaufort]]. He was immediately appointed Deputy Minister of Primary Industries in the government of [[Mahathir Mohamad]]. He shifted to, and won, the seat of [[Kimanis (federal constituency)|Kimanis]] in the [[2004 Malaysian general election|2004 general election]], and became Deputy Minister for Plantation Industries and Commodities. After winning re-election in the [[2008 Malaysian general election|2008 general election]], Prime Minister [[Abdullah Ahmad Badawi]] appointed him as Deputy Transport Minister. However, Anifah refused, saying he felt it was \"time to make way\" for someone else. Reports indicated this was the first time anyone had refused an appointment as Deputy Minister after the appointment had already been made public.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nst.com.my/Current_News/NST/Tuesday/Frontpage/20080318235303/Article/index_html|title= Anifah Aman springs surprise, declines deputy minister's post|work=[[Bernama]]|publisher=[[New Straits Times]]|date=18 March 2008|accessdate=18 March 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080321210127/http://www.nst.com.my/Current_News/NST/Tuesday/Frontpage/20080318235303/Article/index_html|archivedate=21 March 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> A day later, the ''[[New Straits Times]]'' reported that Anifah and another proposed Deputy Minister, Tengku Azlan Abu Bakar, had \"thrown a tantrum ... claiming they are 'senior enough' to be made full ministers\". Abdullah reportedly told them that he had \"picked the best people\", leading to their resignations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nst.com.my/Current_News/NST/Wednesday/National/2190570/Article|title=Two 'seniors' upset over positions|publisher=New Straits Times|date=19 March 2008|accessdate=19 March 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080324112700/http://www.nst.com.my/Current_News/NST/Wednesday/National/2190570/Article|archivedate=24 March 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAfter [[Najib Razak]] replaced Abdullah as Prime Minister in 2009, Anifah was promoted from the backbench to the Cabinet as Minister for Foreign Affairs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thesundaily.my/node/156935|title=Anifah touched to be given important portfolio|work=Bernama|publisher=[[The Sun (Malaysia)|The Sun]]|date=11 April 2009|accessdate=18 May 2018}}</ref> During Anifah's tenure as Foreign Minister, Malaysia won election as a non-permanent member of the [[United Nations Security Council]] for the 2015\u20132016 term.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://malaysiaunsc.kln.gov.my/index.php/malaysia-at-the-unsc/background|title=Malaysia at the UNSC|publisher=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Malaysia]]|accessdate=18 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nAmid retaining his Kimanis seat for the fourth consecutive term in the [[2018 Malaysian general election|2018 general election]] (GE14) which saw the downfall of BN's federal and state governments, Anifah announced his resignation from UMNO to be an independent MP in September 2018.<ref name=QuitUMNO/> On 16 August 2019, the Malaysian Election Court however has voided his win in the GE14 after the court found serious discrepancies in the conduct of the election process by the [[Election Commission of Malaysia|Election Commission]] (EC).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2019/08/17/anifah-aman-loses-kimanis-seat|title=Anifah Aman loses Kimanis seat|publisher= [[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|author=Muguntan Vanar|date=17 August 2019|access-date=10 September 2019}}</ref> He decided not to contest the [[2020 Kimanis by-election]] called to focus on the subsequent 15th General Election instead.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.malaymail.com/amp/news/malaysia/2019/12/19/anifah-confirms-wont-contest-kimanis-by-election-but-to-return-in-ge15/1820690?|title=Anifah confirms won\u2019t contest Kimanis by-election but to return in GE15|publisher=[[Malay Mail]]|author=|date=19 December 2019|access-date=19 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Election results ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ '''[[Dewan Rakyat|Parliament of Malaysia]]''': [[Beaufort (federal constituency)|Beaufort]], Sabah<ref name=\"election results\">{{cite web|url=http://semak.spr.gov.my/spr/laporan/5_KedudukanAkhir.php|title=Keputusan Pilihan Raya Umum Parlimen/Dewan Undangan Negeri|publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]]|accessdate=18 May 2018}} Percentage figures based on total turnout (including votes for candidates not listed).</ref>\n!|Year\n!colspan=2|Government\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!colspan=2|Opposition\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n|-\n|[[1999 Malaysian general election|1999]]\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|{{nowrap|'''Anifah Aman'''}} ([[United Malays National Organisation|UMNO]])\n|align=\"right\" |16,009\n|64%\n|{{Party shading/Keadilan}} |\n|Ak Aliuddin Pg ([[United Sabah Party|PBS]])\n|align=\"right\" |9,209\n|36%\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ '''[[Dewan Rakyat|Parliament of Malaysia]]''': [[Kimanis (federal constituency)|Kimanis]], Sabah<ref name=\"election results\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://election.thestar.com.my/sabah.html|title=Sabah [Parliament Results]|publisher=The Star|accessdate=18 May 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180517234741/https://election.thestar.com.my/sabah.html|archivedate=18 May 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n!|Year\n!colspan=2|Government\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!colspan=2|Opposition\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n|-\n|[[2004 Malaysian general election|2004]]\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|{{nowrap|'''Anifah Aman'''}} ([[United Malays National Organisation|UMNO]])\n|align=\"right\" |9,655\n|66%\n|{{Party shading/Keadilan}} |\n|Awang Tengah Awang Amin ([[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|PKR]])\n|align=\"right\" |4,547\n|31%\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[2008 Malaysian general election|2008]]\n| rowspan=2 {{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n| rowspan=2|{{nowrap|'''Anifah Aman'''}} ([[United Malays National Organisation|UMNO]])\n| rowspan=2 align=\"right\" |10,242\n| rowspan=2|59%\n|{{Party shading/Keadilan}} |\n|Ismail Bongsu ([[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|PKR]])\n|align=\"right\" |1,615\n|9%\n|-\n|{{Party shading/Independent}} |\n|Jaafar Ismail ([[Independent (politician)|IND]])\n|align=\"right\" |4,789\n|28%\n|-\n|[[2013 Malaysian general election|2013]]\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|'''Anifah Aman''' ([[United Malays National Organisation|UMNO]])\n|align=\"right\" |13,754\n|61%\n|{{Party shading/Keadilan}} |\n|Jaafar Ismail ([[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|PKR]])\n|align=\"right\" |8,031\n|35%\n|-\n|[[2018 Malaysian general election|2018]]\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|{{nowrap|'''Anifah Aman'''}} ([[United Malays National Organisation|UMNO]])\n|align=\"right\" |11,942\n|40.3%<sup>2</sup>\n|{{Party shading/Sabah Heritage Party}} |\n|Karim Bujang ([[Sabah Heritage Party|WARISAN]])\n|align=\"right\" |11,786\n|39.8%<sup>2</sup>\n|-\n| colspan=\"9\" |{{small|Notes:<br />Table excludes votes for candidates who finished in third place or lower.<br /><sup>2</sup> Different % used for 2018 election.}}\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n* {{Flag|Pahang}} :\n** [[File:MY-PAH Order of the Crown of Pahang - Knight Companion - DIMP.svg|50px]] Knight Companion of the [[Orders, decorations, and medals of Pahang|Order of the Crown of Pahang]] (DIMP) - '''Dato'''' (2004)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theborneopost.com/2011/10/01/highest-state-award-for-eight/|date=26 October 2004|accessdate=14 September 2018|publisher=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|title=Sultan of Pahang's 74th birthday honours list|work=}}</ref>\n** [[File:MY-PAH Order of Sultan Ahmad Shah of Pahang - Grand Knight - SSAP.svg|50px]] Grand Knight of the [[Orders, decorations, and medals of Pahang|Order of Sultan Ahmad Shah of Pahang]] (SSAP) - '''Dato' Sri''' (2009)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2009/10/24/1114-to-receive-pahang-honours/|date=24 October 2009|accessdate=14 September 2018|publisher=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|title=1,114 to receive Pahang honours|work=}}</ref>\n* {{Flag|Sabah}} :\n** [[File:MY-SAB Order of Kinabalu - PGDK.svg|50px]] Commander of the [[Order of Kinabalu]] (PGDK) - '''Datuk''' (1998)\n** [[File:MY-SAB Order of Kinabalu - SPDK.svg|50px]] Grand Commander of the [[Order of Kinabalu]] (SPDK) - '''Datuk Seri Panglima''' (2011)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theborneopost.com/2011/10/01/highest-state-award-for-eight/|date=1 October 2011|accessdate=14 September 2018|publisher=[[Borneo Post]]|title=Highest state award for eight|work=Sandra Sokial}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of foreign ministers in 2017]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{First Najib cabinet}}\n{{Second Najib cabinet}}\n{{Portal bar|Malaysia|Biography|Politics}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aman, Anifah}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Sabah]]\n[[Category:Kadazan-Dusun people]]\n[[Category:Malaysian Muslims]]\n[[Category:Independent politicians in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:United Malays National Organisation politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Dewan Rakyat]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Foreign ministers of Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Buckingham]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of Kinabalu]]\n[[Category:Grand Commanders of the Order of Kinabalu]]\n[[Category:21st-century Malaysian politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=May 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Malay name|Anifah|Aman}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[Malay titles#Honorary styles|Yang Berbahagia]] [[Malay titles#Datuk Sri|Datuk Seri Panglima]]\n| name             = Anifah Aman\n| native_name      = \u0627\u0646\u064a\u0641\u0647 \u0628\u0646 \u0627\u0645\u0627\u0646 @ \u062d\u0646\u064a\u0641\u0641 \u0639\u0627\u0645\u0645\u0646\n| honorific-suffix = {{small|[[Order of Kinabalu#Commander|SPDK]] [[Orders, decorations, and medals of Pahang|SSAP]] [[Orders, decorations, and medals of Pahang|DIMP]]}}\n| image            = Anifah Aman meeting Iranian FM Javad Zarif(Cropped).jpg\n| caption          =\n| office           = [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Malaysia)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]]\n| monarch = [[Mizan Zainal Abidin of Terengganu|Mizan Zainal Abidin]]<br />[[Abdul Halim of Kedah|Abdul Halim]]<br />[[Muhammad V of Kelantan|Muhammad V]]\n| term_start       = 10 April 2009\n| term_end         = 10 May 2018\n| primeminister    = [[Najib Razak]]\n| deputy           = [[Reezal Merican Naina Merican]] <br/> A. Kohillan Pillay (2009-2013) <br/> [[Lee Chee Leong]] (2009-2010) <br/> [[Richard Riot Jaem]] (2010-2013) <br/> [[Hamzah Zainudin]] (2013-2015) <br/> [[Reezal Merican Naina Merican]] (2015-2018)\n| predecessor      = [[Rais Yatim]]\n| successor        = [[Saifuddin Abdullah]]\n| constituency = [[Kimanis (federal constituency)|Kimanis]]\n| office1 = [[Ministry of Primary Industries (Malaysia)|Deputy Minister of Plantation Industries and Commodities]]\n| term_start1 = 15 December 1999\n| term_end1 = 18 March 2008 <br/> {{small|as Deputy Minister of Primary Industries : 15 December 1999-26 March 2004}}\n| minister1 = [[Lim Keng Yaik]] {{small|as Minister of Primary Industries}} (1999-2004) <br/> [[Peter Chin Fah Kui]] (2004-2008)\n| monarch1 = [[Salahuddin of Selangor|Salahuddin]]<br /> [[Sirajuddin of Perlis|Sirajuddin]]<br />Mizan Zainal Abidin\n| primeminister1 = [[Mahathir Mohamad]]<br />  [[Abdullah Ahmad Badawi]]\n| constituency1 = [[Kimanis (federal constituency)|Kimanis]]\n| successor1 = A. Kohillan Pillay\n| predecessor1 = [[Hishammuddin Hussein]]<br />{{small|as Deputy Minister of Primary Industries}}\n| constituency_MP2 = [[Kimanis (federal constituency)|Kimanis]]\n| parliament2      = Malaysian\n| term_start2      = 22 March 2004\n| term_end2        = 16 August 2019\n| majority2        = 5,108 ([[2004 Malaysian general election|2004]])<br />5,453 ([[2008 Malaysian general election|2008]])<br />5,723 ([[2013 Malaysian general election|2013]])<br />156 ([[2018 Malaysian general election|2018]])\n| predecessor4     = Nurnikman Abdullah\n| successor4       = Mohamad Alamin\n| constituency_MP5 = [[Beaufort (federal constituency)|Beaufort]]\n| parliament5      = Malaysian\n| term_start5      = 30 November 1999\n| term_end5        = 21 March 2004\n| majority5        = 6,800 ([[1999 Malaysian general election|1999]])\n| predecessor5     = Nurnikman Abdullah\n| successor5       = [[Azizah Mohd Dun]]\n| birth_name       = Anifah bin Aman @ Haniff Amman \n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1953|11|16}}\n| birth_place      = [[Keningau]], [[Crown Colony of North Borneo]]\n| residence        =\n| death_date       =\n| death_ place     =\n| party            = [[United Malays National Organisation]] (until 2018) <br /> [[Independent politician|Independent]] (2018-present)\n| otherparty       = *[[Barisan Nasional]] (BN) (until 2018)\n*[[United Alliance]] (2018-present)\n| occupation       = [[Politician]]\n| relations        = [[Musa Aman]] (elder [[Half sibling|half brother]])\n| spouse           = Siti Rubiah Abdul Samad\n| children         = 3 sons\n| alma_mater       = [[University College of Buckingham]]\n| website          =\n| footnotes        =\n}}\n'''Anifah bin Haji Aman''' ([[Jawi alphabet|Jawi]]: \u0627\u0646\u064a\u0641\u0647 \u0628\u0646 \u0627\u0645\u0627\u0646 @ \u062d\u0646\u064a\u0641\u0641 \u0639\u0627\u0645\u0645\u0646; born 16 November 1953) is a [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]] politician who had served as the [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Malaysia)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]] of Malaysia from April 2009 to May 2018. Anifah is also the former [[Dewan Rakyat|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Beaufort (federal constituency)|Beaufort]] (1999-2004) and [[Kimanis (federal constituency)|Kimanis]] (2004-2019) in [[Sabah]]. He was a former member of the [[United Malays National Organisation]] (UMNO) which is part of the [[Barisan Nasional]] (BN) coalition, until he quit to be an [[Independent politician]] in 2018.<ref name=QuitUMNO>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/09/19/anifah-i-quit-umno-in-the-interest-of-sabah-rights|title=Anifah: I quit Umno in the interest of Sabah rights|publisher= [[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|author=Muguntan Vanar|date=19 September 2018 |access-date=15 December 2018}}</ref>.\n\n== Personal life ==\nAnifah is married to Siti Rubiah Abdul Samad and has 3 sons. His second wife is Sophia Mohd Noor and has a daughter. He is the younger [[Half sibling|half brother]] of former [[Chief Minister of Sabah]], [[Musa Aman]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2008/03/20/dont-read-too-much-into-why-anifah-declined-post-says-big-brother-musa-aman/|title=Don\u2019t read too much into why Anifah declined post, says big brother Musa Aman|publisher=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|date=20 March 2008|accessdate=18 May 2018|quote=Sabah Chief Minister Datuk Musa Aman said his younger brother Datuk Anifah Aman had declined the Deputy Minister\u2019s post as he had served in that capacity for two terms.}}</ref> His nephew, [[Yamani Hafez Musa]] who is Musa's son; is the MP for [[Sipitang]].\n\n== Political career ==\nAnifah was first elected to Parliament in [[1999 Malaysian general election|1999 general election]], winning the seat of [[Beaufort (federal constituency)|Beaufort]]. He was immediately appointed Deputy Minister of Primary Industries in the government of [[Mahathir Mohamad]]. He shifted to, and won, the seat of [[Kimanis (federal constituency)|Kimanis]] in the [[2004 Malaysian general election|2004 general election]], and became Deputy Minister for Plantation Industries and Commodities. After winning re-election in the [[2008 Malaysian general election|2008 general election]], Prime Minister [[Abdullah Ahmad Badawi]] appointed him as Deputy Transport Minister. However, Anifah refused, saying he felt it was \"time to make way\" for someone else. Reports indicated this was the first time anyone had refused an appointment as Deputy Minister after the appointment had already been made public.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nst.com.my/Current_News/NST/Tuesday/Frontpage/20080318235303/Article/index_html|title= Anifah Aman springs surprise, declines deputy minister's post|work=[[Bernama]]|publisher=[[New Straits Times]]|date=18 March 2008|accessdate=18 March 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080321210127/http://www.nst.com.my/Current_News/NST/Tuesday/Frontpage/20080318235303/Article/index_html|archivedate=21 March 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> A day later, the ''[[New Straits Times]]'' reported that Anifah and another proposed Deputy Minister, Tengku Azlan Abu Bakar, had \"thrown a tantrum ... claiming they are 'senior enough' to be made full ministers\". Abdullah reportedly told them that he had \"picked the best people\", leading to their resignations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nst.com.my/Current_News/NST/Wednesday/National/2190570/Article|title=Two 'seniors' upset over positions|publisher=New Straits Times|date=19 March 2008|accessdate=19 March 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080324112700/http://www.nst.com.my/Current_News/NST/Wednesday/National/2190570/Article|archivedate=24 March 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAfter [[Najib Razak]] replaced Abdullah as Prime Minister in 2009, Anifah was promoted from the backbench to the Cabinet as Minister for Foreign Affairs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thesundaily.my/node/156935|title=Anifah touched to be given important portfolio|work=Bernama|publisher=[[The Sun (Malaysia)|The Sun]]|date=11 April 2009|accessdate=18 May 2018}}</ref> During Anifah's tenure as Foreign Minister, Malaysia won election as a non-permanent member of the [[United Nations Security Council]] for the 2015\u20132016 term.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://malaysiaunsc.kln.gov.my/index.php/malaysia-at-the-unsc/background|title=Malaysia at the UNSC|publisher=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Malaysia]]|accessdate=18 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nAmid retaining his Kimanis seat for the fourth consecutive term in the [[2018 Malaysian general election|2018 general election]] (GE14) which saw the downfall of BN's federal and state governments, Anifah announced his resignation from UMNO to be an independent MP in September 2018.<ref name=QuitUMNO/> On 16 August 2019, the Malaysian Election Court however has voided his win in the GE14 after the court found serious discrepancies in the conduct of the election process by the [[Election Commission of Malaysia|Election Commission]] (EC).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2019/08/17/anifah-aman-loses-kimanis-seat|title=Anifah Aman loses Kimanis seat|publisher= [[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|author=Muguntan Vanar|date=17 August 2019|access-date=10 September 2019}}</ref> He decided not to contest the [[2020 Kimanis by-election]] called to focus on the subsequent 15th General Election instead.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.malaymail.com/amp/news/malaysia/2019/12/19/anifah-confirms-wont-contest-kimanis-by-election-but-to-return-in-ge15/1820690?|title=Anifah confirms won\u2019t contest Kimanis by-election but to return in GE15|publisher=[[Malay Mail]]|author=|date=19 December 2019|access-date=19 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Election results ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ '''[[Dewan Rakyat|Parliament of Malaysia]]''': [[Beaufort (federal constituency)|Beaufort]], Sabah<ref name=\"election results\">{{cite web|url=http://semak.spr.gov.my/spr/laporan/5_KedudukanAkhir.php|title=Keputusan Pilihan Raya Umum Parlimen/Dewan Undangan Negeri|publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]]|accessdate=18 May 2018}} Percentage figures based on total turnout (including votes for candidates not listed).</ref>\n!|Year\n!colspan=2|Government\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!colspan=2|Opposition\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n|-\n|[[1999 Malaysian general election|1999]]\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|{{nowrap|'''Anifah Aman'''}} ([[United Malays National Organisat